To create a visualisation will i be using ggplot. ggplot is a system of decleratively creating graphics, based on the data provided. In this case will the data be the uploaded casualties file, that i have created.

casualties %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = log10(casualties_total)))+
  geom_col()+
  theme_classic() %>% 
  labs(title = "Casualties in World war 2",
       x = "Country names",
       y = "Number of casualties")+
  coord_flip()

It has now become easier to read the country names, but it is still hard to read the numbers. At the moment Rstudio i reading the numbers as characters instead of numeric. I use gsub to remove all the . When i have all the . removed can i get the program to read the numbers as numeric instead of as characters. this is done with as.numeric To make it easier to read the numbers can i use the code.

options(scipen=999)

casualties_EU$casualties_total <- gsub("[.]","",casualties_EU$casualties_total)
casualties_EU$casualties_total <- as.numeric(casualties_EU$casualties_total)

casualties_EU %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = log10(casualties_total)))+
  geom_col()+
  theme_classic() %>% 
  labs(title = "Casualties in EU doing World war 2",
       x = "Country names",
       y = "Number of casualties (log10)")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
 coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

I am using log10 to make the numbers stand closer together. I have visualised to of the numbers, to show what log10 means. 2=10^2 4=10^4

Now will i make the graph easier to read by sorting the countries

options(scipen=999)

Because the casualties are in numbers (log10) will it be hard to compare the different countries. I estimate that the countries who have a bigger population number also will have a higher death number, then the smaller countries.

I have created a column that shows percentage (Casualties_total / Population_1939) and use this to look at what country lost the most people. But i have also created a column that shows how many people died per. 100.000.

These (percentage and the number of people that died per. 100.000) can be used to compare the countries. I will be using the number of casualties per. 100.000 citizens.

casualties_EU %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Country, casualties_100000),  y = casualties_100000))+
  geom_col()+
  theme_classic() %>% 
  labs(title = "Casualties in EU doing World war 2",
       x = "Country names",
       y = "Number of casualties per. 100.000")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
 coord_flip()
